04617nam a22007215i 9780691187365DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911873657 a10.1515/97806911873652doi  a(DE-B1597)501571  a(OCoLC)1076408571  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHD9747.I83bN674 2007eb 7aBUS0230002bisacsh 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a338.4/7739272231 aGaggio, Dario, eauthor.10aIn Gold We Trust :bSocial Capital and Economic Change in the Italian Jewelry Towns /cDario Gaggio. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION. The Political Economy of Small-Scale Industrialization in Twentieth-Century Italy -- tCHAPTER 1. The Socialists' "City of Gold": Valenza Po's Jewelry Industry from the 1890S to the Fascist Era -- tCHAPTER 2. Negotiating the Economic Miracle: Valenza Po's Jewelry Industry in the Decades after World War II -- tCHAPTER 3. From Craftsmen to Craftsmen: The Development of Vicenza's Jewelry Industry -- tCHAPTER 4. A Pyramid of Trust: The Development of Arezzo's Jewelry Industry -- tCHAPTER 5. The Epistemology of Craftsmanship: Patterns of Style and Skill Formation -- tCHAPTER 6. Constructing Locality: The Jewelry Towns, the International Market, and the Italian State -- tCHAPTER 7. Between Development and Decline: Jewelry Work from an International Perspective -- tConclusion -- tIndex  aIn Gold We Trust is a historical and sociological account of how, by the late 1960s, three small Italian towns had come to lead the world in the production of gold jewelry--even though they had virtually no jewelry industry less than a century before, and even though Italy had western Europe's most restrictive gold laws. It is a distinctive but paradigmatic story of how northern Italy performed its post-World War II economic miracle by creating localized but globally connected informal economies, in which smuggling, tax evasion, and the violation of labor standards coexisted with ongoing deliberation over institutional change and the benefits of political participation. The Italian gold jewelry industry thrived, Dario Gaggio argues, because the citizens of these towns--Valenza Po in Piedmont, Vicenza in the Veneto, and Arezzo in Tuscany--uneasily mixed familial affection, political loyalties, and the instrumental calculation of the market, blurring the distinction between private interests and public good. But through a comparison with the jewelry district of Providence, Rhode Island, Gaggio also shows that these Italian towns weren't unique in the ways they navigated the challenges posed by the embeddedness of economic action in the fabric of social life. By drawing from a variety of disciplinary backgrounds, ranging from economic sociology to political theory, Gaggio recasts the meanings of trust, embeddedness, and social capital, and challenges simple dichotomies between northern and southern Italy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aGold industryzItaly, Northern. 0aJewelry tradezItaly, Northern. 0aSocial capital (Sociology)zItaly, Northern. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187365zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187365.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN